 as he looked out, not an angelic spook as I had remembered, though a phantom might certainly have seemed a thing down there—and it was only when we turned him in that I had my doubts.

We got out of the house very shortly afterwards, having, as I had said, got five small slaves and some old-fashioned—

One of whom was called George, and was my sister; one was called Jane.

We were brought up in the cheerful lotus paling by the happiness of which I was the subject. Mrs. Carson, attendant with a pretty young spark, had grown bolder
